\title{Scientific Schematics}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Create publication-quality scientific diagrams using Nano Banana Pro AI with smart iterative refinement. Uses Gemini 3 Pro for quality review. Only regenerates if quality is below threshold for your document type. Specialized in neural network architectures, system diagrams, flowcharts, biological pathways, and complex scientific visualizations."}

\subtree{
\title{Scientific Schematics and Diagrams}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{Scientific schematics and diagrams transform complex concepts into clear visual representations for publication. \strong{This skill uses Nano Banana Pro AI for diagram generation with Gemini 3 Pro quality review.}}

\p{\strong{How it works:}}

\ul{
\li{Describe your diagram in natural language}
\li{Nano Banana Pro generates publication-quality images automatically}
\li{\strong{Gemini 3 Pro reviews quality} against document-type thresholds}
\li{\strong{Smart iteration}: Only regenerates if quality is below threshold}
\li{Publication-ready output in minutes}
\li{No coding, templates, or manual drawing required}
}

\p{\strong{Quality Thresholds by Document Type:}}

\pre{\startverb
| Document Type | Threshold | Description |
|---------------|-----------|-------------|
| journal | 8.5/10 | Nature, Science, peer-reviewed journals |
| conference | 8.0/10 | Conference papers |
| thesis | 8.0/10 | Dissertations, theses |
| grant | 8.0/10 | Grant proposals |
| preprint | 7.5/10 | arXiv, bioRxiv, etc. |
| report | 7.5/10 | Technical reports |
| poster | 7.0/10 | Academic posters |
| presentation | 6.5/10 | Slides, talks |
| default | 7.5/10 | General purpose |
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Simply describe what you want, and Nano Banana Pro creates it.} All diagrams are stored in the figures/ subfolder and referenced in papers/posters.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start: Generate Any Diagram}
\p{Create any scientific diagram by simply describing it. Nano Banana Pro handles everything automatically with \strong{smart iteration}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Generate for journal paper (highest quality threshold: 8.5/10)
python scripts/generate_schematic.py "CONSORT participant flow diagram with 500 screened, 150 excluded, 350 randomized" -o figures/consort.png --doc-type journal

# Generate for presentation (lower threshold: 6.5/10 - faster)
python scripts/generate_schematic.py "Transformer encoder-decoder architecture showing multi-head attention" -o figures/transformer.png --doc-type presentation

# Generate for poster (moderate threshold: 7.0/10)
python scripts/generate_schematic.py "MAPK signaling pathway from EGFR to gene transcription" -o figures/mapk_pathway.png --doc-type poster

# Custom max iterations (max 2)
python scripts/generate_schematic.py "Complex circuit diagram with op-amp, resistors, and capacitors" -o figures/circuit.png --iterations 2 --doc-type journal
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{What happens behind the scenes:}}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Generation 1}: Nano Banana Pro creates initial image following scientific diagram best practices}
\li{\strong{Review 1}: \strong{Gemini 3 Pro} evaluates quality against document-type threshold}
\li{\strong{Decision}: If quality >= threshold → \strong{DONE} (no more iterations needed!)}
\li{\strong{If below threshold}: Improved prompt based on critique, regenerate}
\li{\strong{Repeat}: Until quality meets threshold OR max iterations reached}
}

\p{\strong{Smart Iteration Benefits:}}

\ul{
\li{✅ Saves API calls if first generation is good enough}
\li{✅ Higher quality standards for journal papers}
\li{✅ Faster turnaround for presentations/posters}
\li{✅ Appropriate quality for each use case}
}

\p{\strong{Output}: Versioned images plus a detailed review log with quality scores, critiques, and early-stop information.}

\subtree{
\title{Configuration}
\p{Set your OpenRouter API key:}

\pre{\startverb
export OPENROUTER_API_KEY='your_api_key_here'
\stopverb}

\p{Get an API key at: https://openrouter.ai/keys}
}

\subtree{
\title{AI Generation Best Practices}
\p{\strong{Effective Prompts for Scientific Diagrams:}}

\p{✓ \strong{Good prompts} (specific, detailed):}

\ul{
\li{"CONSORT flowchart showing participant flow from screening (n=500) through randomization to final analysis"}
\li{"Transformer neural network architecture with encoder stack on left, decoder stack on right, showing multi-head attention and cross-attention connections"}
\li{"Biological signaling cascade: EGFR receptor → RAS → RAF → MEK → ERK → nucleus, with phosphorylation steps labeled"}
\li{"Block diagram of IoT system: sensors → microcontroller → WiFi module → cloud server → mobile app"}
}

\p{✗ \strong{Avoid vague prompts}:}

\ul{
\li{"Make a flowchart" (too generic)}
\li{"Neural network" (which type? what components?)}
\li{"Pathway diagram" (which pathway? what molecules?)}
}

\p{\strong{Key elements to include:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Type}: Flowchart, architecture diagram, pathway, circuit, etc.}
\li{\strong{Components}: Specific elements to include}
\li{\strong{Flow/Direction}: How elements connect (left-to-right, top-to-bottom)}
\li{\strong{Labels}: Key annotations or text to include}
\li{\strong{Style}: Any specific visual requirements}
}

\p{\strong{Scientific Quality Guidelines} (automatically applied):}

\ul{
\li{Clean white/light background}
\li{High contrast for readability}
\li{Clear, readable labels (minimum 10pt)}
\li{Professional typography (sans-serif fonts)}
\li{Colorblind-friendly colors (Okabe-Ito palette)}
\li{Proper spacing to prevent crowding}
\li{Scale bars, legends, axes where appropriate}
}
}
}

